{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17632000","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17632000"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T17:35:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T17:35:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17413"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17413","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17413"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.05,0,0,0.9]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10103"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70525"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10103","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10103"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17413"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55989"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"5326"},{"type":"tags","id":"5538"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23666"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23671"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70525","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/70525"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EHealthcare systems must make decisions about how to allocate limited medical resources across populations with different needs and circumstances.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the principle of distributive justice in healthcare?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Equal distribution of resources regardless of need","Distribution based solely on ability to pay","Priority given to those with highest social status","Allocation determined by first-come first-served basis","Fair allocation of resources based on medical need and benefit"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFair allocation of resources based on medical need and benefit\u003C/strong\u003E represents distributive justice in healthcare. This approach considers both the equitable distribution of limited resources and the potential benefit to individuals and society.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEqual distribution of resources regardless of need\u003C/strong\u003E fails to account for varying medical needs and potential benefits between different individuals and groups.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDistribution based solely on ability to pay\u003C/strong\u003E creates an unfair system that discriminates against those with limited financial means and ignores medical necessity.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPriority given to those with highest social status\u003C/strong\u003E undermines fundamental principles of equity and fairness in healthcare delivery.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAllocation determined by first-come first-served basis\u003C/strong\u003E disadvantages vulnerable populations who may face barriers to accessing healthcare services.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EDistributive justice aims to balance competing demands while ensuring fair access to healthcare resources across the population. This includes considering factors such as medical need, potential benefit, cost-effectiveness, and equity of access.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Distributive justice in healthcare refers to the fair allocation of limited medical resources across a population.","The four main principles of medical ethics are autonomy, beneficence, non-maleficence, and justice.","Healthcare justice considers both equality (treating everyone the same) and equity (providing resources based on need)."],"references":["Shultz JM, Sullivan LM, Galea S. Public Health: An Introduction to the Science and Practice of Population Health. Springer Publishing Company; 2021."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55989"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17413"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"55989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/55989"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-15T19:00:47+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-04T00:10:33+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10103"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"70525"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"5326","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5326"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf0f","name":"Public Health","syn